NSAID INTOXICATION, VULTURE - ASIA (02): KETOPROFEN, POTENTIAL HAZARD
*********************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

Date: Thu 10 Dec 2009
From: Eric Klpahake <dreklaphake@msn.com> [edited]


Re: ProMED-mail NSAID intoxication, vulture - Asia: ketoprofen,
potential hazard 20091210.4204
----------------------------------------------------------------------
I have some concerns with the statement that meloxicam is a "safe"
NSAID for these birds to ingest. The tests run on these birds to
assess for kidney damage -- uric acid levels -- are extremely crude
indicators of kidney disease in birds, often not elevating until 70
percent + of total kidney function is compromised. It may be more
meaningful to perform more advanced assessments of kidney function
through endoscopic biopsy or renal scintigraphy. Or as hard as it is
to lose any of these birds, one should sacrifice high-level-exposed
birds and perform pathological assessments. My concern is that
"recommending meloxicam" as safe -- then finding later that it causes
a long slow renal function decline impacting successful reproduction
and survival of other health conditions -- may be counter-productive.

Each bird species is different in their response to this drug, so
pharmokinetic studies would also be useful to assess the properties
of this drug in these species. They also did not look at the effect
variation on age, perhaps nestlings being fed by parents
regurgitating the drug may be prone to renal failure.

Unless there is unpublished peer-reviewed data out there to support
safety, perhaps it would be better to state "meloxicam seems to be a
safer NSAID for these vultures to ingest, assuming some form of this
class of pharmaceuticals needs to be used." One needs only look at a
drug like acetaminophen (not an NSAID) or rofecoxib (Vioxx) in humans
to see where these drugs can seem safe but whose safety
recommendations change over time.

References
----------
1. Pereira ME, Werther K: Evaluation of the renal effects of flunixin
meglumine, ketoprofen and meloxicam in budgerigars (_Melopsittacus
undulates_). Vet Rec. 2007 Jun 16; 160(24): 844-6.
2. Kirchgessner MS. 2006. Meloxicam. Journal of Exotic Pet Medicine.
2006; 15(4): 281-3.
3. Baert K, Nackaerts J, De Backer P: Disposition of Sodium
Salicylate, Flunixin and Meloxicam after Intravenous Administration
in Ostriches (_Struthio camelus_). Journal of Avian Medicine and
Surgery 2002; 16(2): 123-8.

